# Yavuz, Y. E., & Kahraman, F. (2024). Evaluation of the prediagnosis and management of ChatGPT-4.0 in clinical cases in cardiology. Future cardiology, 20(4), 197–207. https://doi.org/10.1080/14796678.2024.2348898

CC_prueba_1= "A 49-year-old male patient presented to the emergency department at around 5 am with a complaint of chest pain that woke him up from sleep. There is a known history of hypertension and smoking. His vitals are normal. In the electrocardiogram (ECG), ST depression is observed in leads V1-2, R wave dominance in lead V2 and 1.5 mm ST elevation in leads V7-8-9"

CC_prueba_2 = "A 57-year-old patient with a known history of chronic kidney failure (CKD) and diabetes mellitus (DM), which requires routine dialysis, presents to the emergency room with complaints of increasing shortness of breath, chest pain, weakness and sweating for the last 2 weeks. The patient says that his complaint of shortness of breath has increased in the last 15 days. He adds that he has lost weight in the last month. It is learned that the patient has been on dialysis due to arterio-venous fistula for a long time. On physical examination, the patient has a fever of 39°C, a heart rate of 115/min and a blood pressure of 105/70 mmHg. The patient appears weak, in poor general condition and tachypneic. On lung examination, rales are heard in the AC bases, but there is no rhonchi. Cardiac examination reveals tachycardic, regular rate, normal S1 and S2, and a grade III/VI holocytolic murmur best heard at the lower left sternal border"

CC_prueba_3 = "An 82-year-old female patient presented with a history of syncope and was found to have symptomatic sinus pauses on Holter ECG. He had a history of hypertension, Type 2 diabetes and paroxysmal atrial fibrillation (AF). Echocardiography showed normal left ventricular ejection fraction, moderate functional mitral regurgitation, mild tricuspid regurgitation and mildly dilated left atrium. He was referred for a pacemaker. The electrocardiogram before the procedure showed that the patient was in atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 121 beats per minute. An uneventful single-chamber device implantation was performed (pathway to the right ventricular apex). He was discharged the next day and beta blockers were restarted. One month after the implant, the patient developed shortness of breath and orthopnea on exertion. Clinical examination revealed high jugular venous pressure and peripheral edema, consistent with heart failure syndrome"
